english:
  title: A Reply to the Stone's Question
  author: Lee Gyou-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A great stone spoke to me, saying: "I am a thing born of heaven, dwelling upon the earth. I rest as secure as an inverted bowl, rooted as firmly as a planted tree. Nothing moves me when things would move me, no person shifts me when they would shift me. I preserve my nature, maintain my integrity—truly, this is joy. Yet you, too, received heaven's mandate and became human. Humans are the noblest of all creatures. Why then do you not liberate your own body? Why do you not accord with your own nature? Constantly you are enslaved by things, constantly pushed about by people. When things tempt you, you sink into them and cannot escape. When things do not come, you despair and find no joy. When people favor you, your spirit expands; when they reject you, it contracts. Have you not lost your original nature and abandoned all principle? Among all creatures that claim to be noble, is this not your fate alone?"

    I smiled and replied: "How did you, a thing, ever come to be? The Buddhist texts say: 'The dulled and benighted spirits transform into wood and stone.' You have already lost your subtle essence and bright illumination, fallen into this obtuse form. Moreover, when the jade of Harmony is split from its rough stone, you too are split along with it. When the jade of Kunlun is burned, you too are consumed in the flames. Should I mount a dragon and ascend to heaven, you must become a stepping stone beneath my feet, ground and worn. Should I feign death and descend into earth, you must become a monument above me, carved and defaced. Is this not being moved by things and having your nature damaged? Yet you mock me for this.

    "I, however, preserve the true reality within while remaining unattached to circumstances without. Though used by things, I harbor no intention toward them. Though moved by people, I offer no resistance. Thus when stirred I move, when called I go. When action is fitting, I act; when stillness is fitting, I am still. There is nothing I cannot do and nothing I must do. Have you not seen the empty boat? I am like that boat. Why then do you accuse me?"

    The stone, ashamed, had no reply.
  footnotes:
    - The 'empty boat' (虛舟) is a famous metaphor from Zhuangzi, illustrating freedom from judgment and resistance—a boat adrift in water causes no anger, but a boat that strikes us provokes our rage. Li Gyou-bo uses it to express the Daoist and Buddhist ideal of acting without attachment or resentment.
    - The references to the Jade of Harmony (和氏之璞) and the Jade of Kunlun (崐岡之玉) are classical Chinese allusions to precious things that remain subject to external forces—they cannot escape being carved, burned, or otherwise transformed by fate and circumstance.
